        <div class="cs-meta">
          <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-k">My Role</div><div class="cs-meta-v">Solo Product Designer — end-to-end</div></div>
          <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-k">Research</div><div class="cs-meta-v">18 user interviews across age groups and reading habits</div></div>
          <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-k">Methods</div><div class="cs-meta-v">User interviews · Affinity mapping · Competitive analysis · Usability testing · User personas</div></div>
          <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-k">Platform</div><div class="cs-meta-v">Consumer Mobile App (iOS-first)</div></div>
          <div class="cs-meta-row"><div class="cs-meta-k">Tools</div><div class="cs-meta-v">Figma · Procreate · Google Forms · Google Slides</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="note-box r d3">
          <div class="note-tag">Why this matters</div>
          <div class="note-txt">"This shows I can design beyond enterprise dashboards. Consumer UX requires a completely different empathy — designing for delight, not just efficiency."</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs-sec">
    <div class="overline r">Research</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h r d1">18 interviews. Three <em>archetypes.</em></h2>
    <div class="cs-grid2" style="margin-top:36px">
      <div class="r d1">
        <div class="cs-body">
          <p>I interviewed 18 avid readers across age groups and reading habits. The questions weren't about what features they wanted — they were about behaviour: how do you decide what to read next? What happens to a book you've finished? What would make you trust a stranger with your favourite book?</p>
          <p>Three patterns emerged consistently: trust in the counterpart, confidence in the book's condition, and the joy of serendipitous discovery. None of the existing platforms (OLX, Facebook Marketplace) served all three. That gap became the design brief.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="r d2">
        <div class="cs-grid3" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:10px">
          <div style="background:var(--chalk2);padding:22px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--rose)">
            <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--rose);margin-bottom:6px">Archetype 01</div>
            <div class="cs-h2" style="font-size:18px">The Curator</div>
            <div class="cs-body-sm">Sells carefully. Selective about buyers. Cares deeply about where their books end up. Needs trust signals and a way to know their books are going to the right person.</div>
          </div>
          <div style="background:var(--chalk2);padding:22px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--sage)">
            <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--sage);margin-bottom:6px">Archetype 02</div>
            <div class="cs-h2" style="font-size:18px">The Serendipitous Reader</div>
            <div class="cs-body-sm">Discovers by mood, not title. Doesn't know what they want until they see it. Needs a discovery experience that matches how readers actually browse — not just search.</div>
          </div>
          <div style="background:var(--chalk2);padding:22px 20px;border-left:3px solid var(--stone)">
            <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--stone);margin-bottom:6px">Archetype 03</div>
            <div class="cs-h2" style="font-size:18px">The Practical Trader</div>
            <div class="cs-body-sm">Just wants fair value, fast. Doesn't attach emotionally to books. Needs a clean, efficient listing and transaction flow — no friction, no storytelling required.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs-sec cs-sec--tint">
    <div class="overline r">Design Process</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h r d1">Research-led, <em>all the way.</em></h2>
    <div class="proc-list r d2">
      <div class="proc-step"><div class="proc-l"><div class="proc-n">01</div><div class="proc-phase">Research</div></div><div class="proc-r"><div class="proc-ttl">18 User Interviews</div><div class="proc-body">Interviewed 18 avid readers across demographics. Key insight: condition and trust were non-negotiable — more important than price or selection. Most participants had been burned by misrepresented book conditions on generic platforms. This single insight drove most of the design decisions.</div></div></div>
      <div class="proc-step"><div class="proc-l"><div class="proc-n">02</div><div class="proc-phase">Synthesis</div></div><div class="proc-r"><div class="proc-ttl">Affinity Mapping → Three Archetypes</div><div class="proc-body">Synthesised research using affinity mapping — grouping behaviours, motivations, and pain points across all 18 participants. Three distinct archetypes emerged, each shaping a different area of the product. Used Google Forms for quantitative validation across a wider set of 40+ readers.</div></div></div>
      <div class="proc-step"><div class="proc-l"><div class="proc-n">03</div><div class="proc-phase">Design</div></div><div class="proc-r"><div class="proc-ttl">End-to-End UI System</div><div class="proc-body">Designed the complete app — home, discovery, listing flow, condition rating, messaging, seller profiles, and transaction. Chose a warm, paper-textured visual language deliberately: BookBarn should feel like a bookshop, not an e-commerce platform. Every colour, font, and illustration decision was intentional and archetype-informed.</div></div></div>
      <div class="proc-step"><div class="proc-l"><div class="proc-n">04</div><div class="proc-phase">Test</div></div><div class="proc-r"><div class="proc-ttl">Usability Testing — Key Finding</div><div class="proc-body">Tested with 8 participants across all three archetypes. The mood-based discovery flow was the most loved feature — and the most confusing to set up as a seller. Iterated the mood-tagging flow three times to reduce friction to under 45 seconds per new listing. The condition rating system was trusted immediately by every participant.</div></div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cs-sec cs-sec--alt">
    <div class="overline r">Key Decisions</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h r d1">Why it looks and feels <em>the way it does.</em></h2>
    <div class="cs-grid3" style="margin-top:44px">
      <div class="r" style="background:var(--chalk2);padding:34px 28px">
        <div style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:38px;font-weight:900;color:var(--chalk3);line-height:1;margin-bottom:12px">01</div>
        <div class="cs-h2">Condition Rating System</div>
        <p class="cs-body-sm">Standard star ratings don't work for books — a 3-star could mean "readable" or "falling apart." I designed a 5-level condition system with visual examples and written descriptions for each level. Every usability test participant immediately trusted it more than any star rating. Trust problem: solved.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="r d1" style="background:var(--chalk2);padding:34px 28px">
        <div style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:38px;font-weight:900;color:var(--chalk3);line-height:1;margin-bottom:12px">02</div>
        <div class="cs-h2">Discover by Mood</div>
        <p class="cs-body-sm">Most readers don't know the title they want — they know how they want to feel. I designed a mood-based discovery flow (cozy, thought-provoking, escapist, intense) as the primary path, with search as secondary. The most-appreciated feature in testing. The Serendipitous Reader archetype was finally served.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="r d2" style="background:var(--chalk2);padding:34px 28px">
        <div style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:38px;font-weight:900;color:var(--chalk3);line-height:1;margin-bottom:12px">03</div>
        <div class="cs-h2">Seller Trust Profile</div>
        <p class="cs-body-sm">On BookBarn you're not buying from a stranger — you're buying from a reader. Seller profiles show reading history, favourite genres, and past listing reviews. It turns a transaction into a connection between people who genuinely care about the same thing. The Curator archetype demanded this, and everyone benefited from it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="next-proj r" onclick="go('omni')">
    <div><div class="np-label">Back to start</div><div class="np-title">Omni Connect →</div></div>
    <div class="np-arr">→</div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
// cursor
const cur=document.getElementById('cur'),ring=document.getElementById('cur-ring');
document.addEventListener('mousemove',e=>{
  const s=`left:${e.clientX}px;top:${e.clientY}px`;
  cur.style.cssText=s;ring.style.cssText=s;
});

// nav
window.addEventListener('scroll',()=>{
  document.getElementById('nav').classList.toggle('solid',scrollY>60);
});

// routing
const pages={
  home:'pg-home',omni:'pg-omni',quloi:'pg-quloi',book:'pg-book'
};
function go(id){
  document.querySelectorAll('.page').forEach(p=>p.classList.remove('active'));
  const el=document.getElementById(pages[id]);
  if(el){el.classList.add('active');window.scrollTo(0,0);setTimeout(reveal,80)}
}
function toAbout(){go('home');setTimeout(()=>document.getElementById('about')?.scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth'}),120)}
function toContact(){go('home');setTimeout(()=>document.getElementById('contact')?.scrollIntoView({behavior:'smooth'}),120)}

// reveal
function reveal(){
  const obs=new IntersectionObserver(entries=>{
    entries.forEach(e=>{if(e.isIntersecting)e.target.classList.add('on')});
  },{threshold:.07,rootMargin:'0px 0px -32px 0px'});
  document.querySelectorAll('.r:not(.on)').forEach(el=>obs.observe(el));
}
reveal();
</script>
